 Kingdom","Bakewell, Derbyshire, England":"Bakewell, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","Chester, Cheshire, England":"Chester, Cheshire, England","Wheelocke,,Cheshire,England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Vernon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Vernon in Eure, France, named from the Gaulish element <i>ver(n)</i> ‘alder’ + the Gallo-Roman locative suffix <i>-o</i> (genitive <i>-ōnis</i>).","French: habitational name from the same place as in 1 above or from any of several other places in France with the same name and etymology."],"variants":[{"name":"Varnon","meanings":["English (Leicestershire and Northamptonshire): variant of   Vernon  ."]}]},{"name":"Eleanor","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ellenor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor  , the result of blending with   Ellen ."]},{"name":"Elenor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]},{"name":"Elinor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor ."]}]},{"name":"Ellen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Helen  , although now no longer associated with that name. Initial <i>H-</i> tended to be added and dropped rather capriciously, leading to many doublets (  compare for example  Esther   and   Hester  ). It is also sometimes used as a short form of   Eleanor  , to which, however, it is unrelated."],"variants":[{"name":"Eleanor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]}]},{"name":"Hulse","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Cheshire and Staffordshire): habitational name from Hulse in Witton (Cheshire), from Middle English <i>holes</i>, plural of <i>hole</i> ‘hole, hollow, depression’ (Old English <i>holh</i>). See   Hole  .","North German (<b>Hülse</b>): topographic name for someone who lived where holly grew, Middle Low German <i>huls</i>, <i>hüls</i>.","American shortened and altered form of Flemish <b>Holsaert</b> (see   Hulsart  ). Compare   Hulce  ,   Huls  , and   Hults   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Hulsart","meanings":["Americanized form of Flemish <b>Holsaert</b>: unexplained. See also   Hulse   3."]},{"name":"Hole","meanings":["From the vocabulary word (Old English <i>hopa</i>) denoting the quality, in particular the Christian quality of expectation in the resurrection and in eternal life. The name was created by the Puritans and has been one of their most successful coinages."]},{"name":"Hults","meanings":["Altered form of   Hulse  , a surname of Flemish (and also of English and German) origin. Compare   Hultz   1.","In some cases also a variant of   Hultz   2, a surname of German origin."]},{"name":"Hulce","meanings":["A female name meaning sweet, pleasant, or gentle. Some say it is the same as Dousie."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Eleanor Ellen Hulse Vernon was born in 1430, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Richard Wheelock in 1449, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died on 21 April 1474, in Bakewell, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 44."},"et":{"1430–21 Apr 1474":"1430–21. aprill 1474","1430–Male":"1430–Surnud","1450–1528":"1450–1528","1430–1474":"1430–1474","1430":"1430","1474":"1474","1450":"1450","1528":"1528","21 Apr 1474":"21. aprill 1474","1449":"1449","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bakewell, Derbyshire, England":"Bakewell, Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Chester, Cheshire, England":"Chester, Cheshire, England","Wheelocke,,Cheshire,England":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1430–21 Apr 1474":"1430–21. huhtikuuta 1474","1430–Male":"1430–Kuollut","1450–1528":"1450–1528","1430–1474":"1430–1474","1430":"1430","1474":"1474","1450":"1450","1528":"1528","21 Apr 1474":"21. huhtikuuta 1474","1449":"1449","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Bakewell, Derbyshire, England":"Bakewell, Derbyshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Chester, Cheshire, England":"Chester, Cheshire, England","Wheelocke,,Cheshire,England":"Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1430–21 Apr 1474":"1430–21 avril 1474","1430–Male":"1430–Dé